### useRef

`useRef` returns a mutable ref object whose `.current` property persists across renders. Unlike state, changing a ref does not trigger a re-render.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useRef } from 'react';

const ref = useRef(initialValue);
// ref.current persists across renders
```

### Use Case 1: Accessing DOM Nodes

```jsx
function AutoFocus() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  }, []);

  return <input ref={inputRef} type="text" />;
}
```

### Use Case 2: Storing Mutable Values

```jsx
function Timer() {
  const intervalRef = useRef(null);

  const start = () => {
    intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {}, 1000);
  };

  const stop = () => {
    clearInterval(intervalRef.current);
  };
}
```

### Use Case 3: Tracking Previous Values

```jsx
function usePrevious(value) {
  const ref = useRef();
  useEffect(() => {
    ref.current = value;
  }, [value]);
  return ref.current;
}
```

| Feature | useState | useRef |
|---------|----------|--------|
| Triggers re-render | Yes | No |
| Persists across renders | Yes | Yes |
| Asynchronous update | Yes | No |

> **Key Point:** useRef is useful for values that need to persist across renders but should not trigger re-renders when changed. Common uses: interval IDs, previous values, and DOM refs.

codeExample:
import { useRef } from 'react';

function ClickCounter() {
  const countRef = useRef(0);

  const handleClick = () => {
    countRef.current += 1;
    console.log(`Clicked ${countRef.current} times`);
  };

  return <button onClick={handleClick}>Click (no re-render)</button>;
}
